    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 3rd with a high-ceiling lineup centered on **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98), who profiles as today\u2019s top play. His matchup against Merrill Kelly is bolstered by an 18% SP skill advantage and a critical wind-out factor that adds 10% to his efficiency, making him a prime candidate for a multi-base outcome. **Junior Caminero** (71.71) and **Trea Turner** (69.28) follow closely as our most reliable engines; **Trea Turner** secures a significant boost from his leadoff spot against the middling Chris Paddack, while **Junior Caminero** finds a favorable dynamic platoon opportunity. We are also capitalizing on the high-contact profile of **Colt Keith** (65.83), who benefits from a leaky Jack Leiter and a strong order position, providing a dual-threat boost to our middle infield production.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was excluding **Jerar Encarnacion**, whose score of 42.40 fell just short of our threshold. While **Jerar Encarnacion** offers situational upside against Steven Matz, he was edged out by the superior park and order-adjusted metrics of our active starters. Meanwhile, caution is warranted regarding **Dillon Dingler** (46.93) and **Hyeseong Kim** (55.71); both face risks today\u2014**Dillon Dingler** is hampered by a significant platoon deficit, and **Hyeseong Kim** must contend with an elite hold pitcher in Dustin May who historically suppresses stolen base attempts. \n\nPlease note that as of this report, all lineup positions remain pending and are modeled on historical trends; **Gary Sanchez** and **Caleb Durbin** are particularly sensitive to these assumptions, with **Caleb Durbin** suffering a negative value adjustment for a projected bottom-of-the-order start. Finally, we continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, who remains on the IL and unavailable for selection, forcing us to rely on our deeper outfield pool to maintain the Zebras' competitive pace in the 5x5 standings.",
